.TH BUNPY-REPL 1 "2026-04-27" "bunpy" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
bunpy-repl \- interactive Python prompt
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B bunpy repl
[\fB--quiet\fR]
.SH DESCRIPTION
Opens the interactive Python prompt. Each chunk is read until a
blank line and then handed to
.BR "bunpy run"
as a one-shot module. v0.0.8 is stateless: chunks do not share
globals. Persistent globals waits for gocopy to grow expression
and call compilation; the CLI surface is stable and will not
change when that lands.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B --quiet
Suppress the startup banner and the
.B >>>
and
.B ...
prompts. Useful for piped stdin and scripted smokes.
.SH META COMMANDS
Lines starting with
.B :
are REPL meta commands and never reach the compiler.
.TP
.B :help
Print the list of REPL commands.
.TP
.BR :quit ", " :exit
Leave the REPL with exit status zero.
.TP
.BI :history " " [N]
Print the last
.I N
history entries (default: all).
.TP
.B :clear
Drop the in-flight buffer.
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
.B BUNPY_HISTORY
Path to the history file. Defaults to
.IR "$HOME/.bunpy_history" .
.TP
.B BUNPY_HISTORY_SIZE
Maximum number of entries (default 1000). Setting this to
.B 0
disables history.
.SH EXIT STATUS
Zero on
.BR :quit ", " :exit ", "
or end of stdin. Non-zero on an internal error (history file I/O,
unreadable stdin). User-side compile errors are reported to stderr
and the loop continues.
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR bunpy (1),
.BR bunpy-run (1).
